flowRoot.flowPara: Dopamine is an inhibitory neurotransmitter. It is strongly associated with reward mechanisms. Cocaine, opium, heroin, alcohol and nicotine increase the levels of dopamine. If it feels good, dopamine neurons are probably involved. Schizophrenia has been shown to involve excessive amounts of dopamine in the frontal lobes. On the contrary, too little dopamine in motor areas is responsible for Parkinson's disease. Recently, it has been noted that low dopamine may relate not only to the unsociability of schizophrenics, but also to social anxiety.
